Michael wrote :

> I really don't think there is any point to working on embodying
> ourselves in a world where we control the physics.  That's
> effectively the case in AgoraMOO.  We control the physics of our
> existing (very virtual world) as it is, and it is precisely this
> that I think we should be moving away from. 

We do and we don't. To the extent that the ultimate 'reality' of
AgoraMOO is under the control of persons, the Rules can control it to
exactly the same extent that they can control persons, i.e. not at
all unless there's a means of enforcement. 

We can hope to have the Rules be enforced in a MUD only to the extent
that we know that the persons controlling the MUD are willing to
abide by the Rules. In this respect there is no difference between
AgoraMOO and Shattered World, since both I and the SW wizards have
indicated willingness to do so. Actually, because the persons who
actually control SW are not Agorans, we will have fewer and weaker
means of enforcement there than we would in AgoraMOO.

The main difference between Shattered World and AgoraMOO is that
there is currently more 'physics' in SW to provide for some acts
that we might be tempted to regulate. This however won't stay the
case, as more participants to AgoraMOO provide code that lets people
'do' interesting 'stuff'.

But conversely, because the 'physics' of SW already regulate a lot of
things, there'll be less incentive to legislate; and because of the
situation of the Agoran community there, I expect the main focus of
activity to be on diplomatic relations with Sanom City, the main area
of SW, rather than on legislative activity regulating individual's
actions.

Scott added :

> In addition, I point out that SW offers us amazing potential for
> _real_ internomic relations (not the sterile stuff that goes on in
> Internomic).

We might offer other Nomics some space on AgoraMOO and derive exactly
the same benefit from that. It would hurt my pride somewhat if Agora,
the 'oldest and largest' Nomic, were to have its virtual world
subordinate to that of smaller game. ;)

> to enforce our jurisdiction.  Initially, this area will probably
> be quite small, and our means of enforcement rather meager.  But we
> can hope to expand. 

Then why not, from the start, choose a world where the means of
enforcement exist and expanson would be easier ? In addition, some
of us already feel SW's 'physics' to be constricting and too RPG
inspired. AgoraMOO doesn't suffer from such disadvantages, and the
'physics' that eventually build there can be set up to suits the
particular needs of our community.

Of course, as I've mentioned, nothing prevents us from inhabiting
both worlds. We can have a Rule Category for Merenth (the place in
Shattered World we're going to settle) and one for AgoraMOO, and
pass Rules regulating both places. Watching how either world gives
rise to different legislative activities can also be an interesting
experiment.


